Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1 & 2. Guard Navigation with a Confirmation Dialog

In your `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` before awaiting the dialog, then call `deferral.Complete()` afterward — otherwise Shell won't wait for your async check.

## 3. Custom "Cancel" Back Button

In `EditProductPage.xaml`, attach a `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel or code-behind
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Since `GoToAsync("..")` produces a `Pop` navigation, the same `OnNavigating` guard will intercept it and show the confirmation dialog before actually navigating away.
